article.headline: Triple-threat Burgess shoots Gamecocks past Lady Rebels
article.linkText: Triple-threat Burgess shoots Gamecocks past Lady Rebels
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- South Carolina had trouble just getting to Arkansas for the Southeastern Conference Tournament and once they got here Mississippi gave the Gamecocks (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) a scare.

Freshman Sarah Burgess came off the bench with a career-high 23 points to lead South Carolina to a 79-64 first-round victory Thursday night over the Lady Rebels, who led 54-53 with 10:12 left.

A charter flight scheduled to leave South Carolina at 6 p.m. Wednesday left late, so Susan Walvius' team didn't arrive in North Little Rock until 4 a.m.

Burgess made sure South Carolina (22-6) wasn't bothered by the late arrival with 8-for-11 shooting from the field, including 7-for-10 on 3-pointers.

``I was just going out there and playing,'' said Burgess, whose previous career high was 15 in the regular-season finale against Ole Miss on Sunday. ``I didn't know I had that many 3s. After about the third one I hit, I knew I was feeling it.''

South Carolina advances to meet No. 10 Mississippi State in the
quarterfinals at 6 p.m. on Friday.

South Carolina trailed Ole Miss (12-16) three times in the
second half, but the Gamecocks took control with a 16-0 run. They
opened and closed the game with runs of 26-10.

   Burgess' 3-pointer with 8:08 remaining gave South Carolina a
58-54 lead and she hit another the next time down the floor.

   ``Burgess hit some big shots and we got caught up and didn't
cover her in a man or a zone,'' Ole Miss coach Ron Aldy said.
``That added a lot of pressure on us. We couldn't help down low and
get out quick enough to cover her.''

   While South Carolina made its 16-0 run, Ole Miss (12-16) missed
seven shots and committed three turnovers before Amber Watts' layup
with about three minutes to go cut South Carolina's lead to 69-56.

``I thought Mississippi really came out and did a great job from
the perimeter and attacking the rim,'' Walvius said. ``They're a
dangerous team. I really felt fortunate to get out of here with a
'W' today.''

   Ole Miss opened the second half with a 14-5 run, capped by
Genice Terry's 3-pointer with 13:07 remaining for a 47-45 lead, its
first of the game. The lead changed hands five times before South
Carolina took over with its 16-0 run.

``After making a couple of plays and a couple of runs and
breaking down their defense we felt a lot of confidence,'' Watts
said. ``We felt if we could have kept that up we could have kept
making runs, but we weren't able to do it.''

   Two players had double-doubles for South Carolina, as center
Petra Ujhelyi scored 16 points and grabbed 13 rebounds, while
Cristina Ciocan had 12 points and 10 assists. Jocelyn Penn added 13
points and eight rebounds for the Gamecocks.

``We were a little tired, but we know we're a great team and we
knew what we had to do to come in here and win this game,'' Penn
said.

Terry led Ole Miss with 18 points and Watts scored 15.

South Carolina's lead was 29-14 with 8:56 left in the half after
Burgess came off the bench and hit three straight 3-pointers.

Ole Miss trimmed the lead to under 10 points with a 17-9 run.
Ashley Johnson scored six points during the spurt and Terry added
five. The Lady Rebels cut the lead to 38-31 when point guard Carletta Brown made a steal and scored on a fast break with 1:50 left in the half.
